title: Multiple-Dose, Dose-Escalation Study to Assess the Safety, Tolerability, Pharmacokinetics and Pharmacodynamics of LY3303560 in Patients With Mild Cognitive Impairment Due to Alzheimer's Disease or Mild to Moderate Alzheimer's Disease
description_brief: The study involves repeated doses of LY3303560 given by infusion for 49 weeks. The study will examine how safe repeated doses of LY3303560 are, whether they cause side effects in participants with mild cognitive impairment or Alzheimer's Disease, and how LY3303560 is handled by the body and acts in the body. This study will last up to 65 weeks, not including screening. Screening is required within 90 days prior to the start of the study.

drug: LY3303560 (zagotenemab) — monoclonal antibody targeting aggregated/pathologic tau
explanation_target: Reason: The trial drug LY3303560 is a monoclonal antibody that binds aggregated (misfolded) tau protein and was developed to reduce/block spread of pathologic tau in Alzheimer’s disease — i.e., it is a biologic that targets AD pathology, consistent with disease-modifying intent. citeturn0search2turn0search5

Act: Key extracted details — repeated IV (and in some cohorts SC) dosing for ~49 weeks / monthly dosing, participant population MCI due to AD or mild–moderate AD, primary aims safety/tolerability/PK/PD. The compound LY3303560 is also known as zagotenemab. These facts map the intervention to a disease-targeted biologic (anti-tau monoclonal antibody). citeturn0search3turn0search5

Reflect: Classification check — because the agent is an antibody (a biologic) directed at aggregated tau (an AD pathological hallmark) and the study assesses pharmacodynamics on tau, the correct category is 'disease-targeted biologic' rather than cognitive enhancer or symptomatic treatment. No evidence in the description that this is a small molecule, a purely symptomatic cognitive enhancer, or a neuropsychiatric-targeted therapy. citeturn0search2turn0search8
Web-search source summary: NCT03518073 / clinical registry lists LY3303560 as zagotenemab (anti-tau antibody) in Phase 2 AD trials. citeturn0search5

Web-search source summary: HRA (UK) study page describes LY3303560 attaching to aggregated tau and reducing spread of tau in preclinical studies; describes 13 monthly doses and use of tau PET. citeturn0search2
Web-search source summary: Clinical trial entry (NCT03019536 / trial listings) and trial descriptions match the user's 49-week repeated-dose design and safety/PK/PD aims. citeturn0search3

Web-search source summary: Alzforum and other summaries discuss zagotenemab (LY3303560) as an anti-tau monoclonal antibody and report trial details/results, supporting that this is an anti-tau biologic program. citeturn0search8turn0search6
explanation_agent: Reason: The investigational agent LY3303560 (zagotenemab) is a humanized monoclonal antibody that preferentially binds misfolded/aggregated extracellular tau with the intent to reduce or block spread of pathologic tau — i.e., the mechanism is directly directed at tau pathology in AD. citeturn0search4turn0search2

Act: Extracted facts from the trial description and sources — drug name/synonym: LY3303560 (zagotenemab); drug type: monoclonal biologic immunotherapy; biological target: aggregated/pathologic tau (soluble tau aggregates / misfolded tau); population and design: MCI due to AD or mild–moderate AD, multiple/ repeated dosing (monthly cohorts / up to ~49 weeks in the Phase 1b multiple-dose study; larger Phase 2 PERISCOPE study used IV Q4W dosing). These details map the intervention to CADRO category B) Tau. citeturn0search8turn0search4turn0search0

Reflect: The classification as B) Tau is consistent and specific: the agent is a disease-targeted biologic whose primary mechanism is anti-tau immunotherapy rather than amyloid, inflammation, symptomatic neurotransmitter modulation, or a multi-target intervention. No information in the description indicates a different primary pathway, so B) Tau is the correct CADRO category. (For completeness: later-phase results reported no meaningful slowing of clinical progression in a Phase 2 trial, but that does not change the mechanistic classification.) citeturn0search5turn0search2

Web-search results used (brief): 1) PubMed Phase Ib paper describing zagotenemab as a monoclonal antibody binding misfolded/aggregated tau and reporting multiple-dose safety/PK up to ~49 weeks. citeturn0search4 2) Alzforum therapeutic entry summarizing zagotenemab (LY3303560) as a humanized anti-tau antibody that binds/neutralizes tau aggregates. citeturn0search2 3) Clinical registry/trial listing (NCT03518073 / PERISCOPE-ALZ) describing LY3303560 (zagotenemab) dosing cohorts and Phase 2 trial design. citeturn0search0 4) NCATS / drug registry entry listing synonyms and the compound identity (LY3303560 = zagotenemab). citeturn0search8 5) News/summary reporting Phase 2 outcome (no significant slowing of decline), provided here only as outcome context, not for mechanistic classification. citeturn0search5
